{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 17:00:26.914181", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and summary\n- Goal: Assess end-to-end health for host access to server-farm services (DNS, load balancer, web servers) over an OSPF-based hierarchical network.\n- High-level result: Layer-2/Layer-3 connectivity and routing appear healthy. DNS connectivity and name resolution are working. However, HTTP application performance shows intermittent, significant server-side latency when accessing the Apache web servers directly (web0.local–web3.local and 10.200.0.3), while the load balancer service (web99.local) is consistently faster. The anomaly localizes to the web servers themselves (application layer), not the network path.\n\nFindings and evidence\n\n1) IP reachability and routing (OSPF transport)\n- End-to-end ICMP tests show 0% loss and low RTTs across subnets:\n  - From user hosts to server-farm nodes:\n    - host_1_1_1_1 -> dns_server (10.200.0.2): 0% loss, avg ~3.26 ms\n    - host_1_1_1_1 -> load_balancer (10.200.0.7): 0% loss, avg ~3.56 ms\n    - host_1_1_1_1 -> web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): 0% loss, avg ~3.39 ms\n    - host_2_1_1_1 -> dns_server: 0% loss, avg ~2.64 ms\n    - host_2_1_1_1 -> load_balancer: 0% loss, avg ~2.82 ms\n    - host_2_1_1_1 -> web_server_0: 0% loss, avg ~3.12 ms\n  - Server-farm nodes can reach access hosts as well (e.g., dhcp_server/dns_server -> 10.1/10.2 hosts, 0% loss, low RTTs).\n- Interpretation: Underlay L2/L3 and OSPF routing are functioning correctly; no signs of path loss or instability.\n\n2) DNS service\n- DNS server reachable from hosts (ICMP OK).\n- Name resolution performance during HTTP tests is generally fast (name lookup ~3–12 ms), with a single outlier at ~61 ms; not enough to explain >1 s delays observed elsewhere.\n- Interpretation: DNS connectivity and resolution for service names are healthy; DNS is unlikely to be the primary cause of the large HTTP TTFB spikes on clients.\n\n3) HTTP service behavior\n- Load balancer (web99.local):\n  - From both hosts: starttransfer ~0.21–0.29 s, total ~1.02–1.09 s (stable across multiple trials).\n- Direct access to Apache web servers:\n  - By name (web0.local–web3.local) and by IP (10.200.0.3):\n    - Intermittent large starttransfer (TTFB) delays frequently around 1.1–1.7 s and occasionally low (0.21–0.50 s).\n    - Examples:\n      - host_1_1_1_1 -> web0.local: TTFB 0.34 s then 1.29 s (total 1.14 s then 2.09 s)\n      - host_2_1_1_1 -> web0.local: TTFB ~1.22–1.32 s (total ~2.02–2.12 s)\n      - host_1_1_1_1 -> web1.local: TTFB 1.71 s then 0.50 s\n      - host_2_1_1_1 -> web1.local: TTFB ~1.49–1.51 s\n      - host_1_1_1_1 -> web2.local: TTFB 0.22 s then 1.22 s\n      - host_1_1_1_1 -> web3.local: TTFB 0.21 s then 1.22 s\n      - host_1_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.3: TTFB ~1.31–1.40 s\n      - host_2_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.3: one fast (0.23 s), one slow (1.30 s)\n- Network-layer indicators during these HTTP tests:\n  - TCP connect times are consistently low (~2–18 ms), and ICMP RTTs are ~2–5 ms, indicating the transport path is not congested or lossy.\n  - Name lookup times are small (few ms) when slow TTFB occurs, showing client-side DNS resolution is not the cause of the >1 s delay.\n\nAssessment of anomalies\n- Anomalous behavior: Intermittent, significant application-layer latency (TTFB ~1.1–1.7 s) when accessing the Apache web servers directly, not observed through the load balancer, and not explained by network latency or client-side DNS lookup.\n- Normal behavior: \n  - Stable, fast service via the load balancer (web99.local).\n  - Healthy L2/L3 reachability and OSPF transport across areas.\n  - DHCP-allocated addresses in expected subnets.\n  - DNS reachable and resolving service names with low latency.\n\nLocalization\n- The anomaly is localized to the Apache web servers (web_server_0–web_server_3).\n- The load balancer and routing infrastructure do not exhibit the same delays.\n- Given low connect times and ICMP RTTs, the underlying network devices (routers/switches) are unlikely to be the source.\n\nLikely root cause\n- Application-level blocking on the web servers prior to sending the first byte. The delay profile (often around ~1–1.5 s) and its intermittent nature are consistent with server-side reverse DNS lookups on client IPs (e.g., Apache HostnameLookups or similar logging/access control lookups) where PTR records are absent/slow, or other per-request synchronous lookups.\n- Because the load balancer path is consistently faster, it likely does not perform the same per-request blocking behavior, further pointing to web server configuration or backend name-resolution behavior as the root cause.\n\nAdditional notes\n- Could not directly verify the inaccessibility of backend web servers behind the load balancer (backend_web_*) from hosts due to lack of their IP visibility in the inventory; however, no evidence suggests policy/routing leakage.\n- OSPF control-plane status was inferred from data-plane reachability; explicit OSPF adjacency/LSDB inspection was not performed since transport tests were clean.\n\nConclusion\n- Network transport and DNS resolution are healthy.\n- Primary issue: Intermittent application-layer latency on Apache web servers, most plausibly due to server-side reverse DNS or similar synchronous lookup behavior. The load balancer service runs normally and is not affected.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 10848, "output_tokens": 5311, "total_tokens": 16159, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 9728}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3840}}}
